 Hi; thanks for the quick response.
 
 > I'm not completely clear on the details as to why myself, but I think
 > that if you want to see stdout, you have to run from a Terminal
 > window.
 
 When I try to Create Executable from
 a file with #lang racket (instead of a
 student language), I get a little dialogue
 box that asks for the type of executable
 (I choose "Distribution") and the base
 (Racket or GRacket).  
 
 If I pick Racket, then instead of a
 whatever.app icon (that, when clicked,
 launches and quits right away), I get a
 folder that contains bin and lib subfolders.
 
 > Inside the .app bundle (aka directory) you'll find (a few directory
 > levels deep) a regular binary that you can just run if you want to see
 > stdout.
 
 Right.  In that situation, the code works
 as expected in the Terminal window.
 
 > I'm pretty sure that this is a non-optimal solution, but I'm not sure
 > that we can do better in the short term.
 
 I'm not desperate for an optimal solution
 in the short term; I won't be teaching this
 for a while.  But I'd really like an optimal
 solution (where a student can click
 Create Executable and seamlessly get
 an app that can be double-clicked to
 run on somebody else's machine) some
 day.  
 
 (Students are already skeptical about 
 learning a language they've never heard
 of.  It significantly bolster's Scheme/Racket's
 credibility if students can write code, turn
 it into an app, and distribute it to their friends
 and relatives seamlessly.)
 
 > If it matters for your classroom, perhaps you should try using the
 > universe teachpack (to get GUI programs) or the module language, where
 > you have more flexibility with the kinds of applications you can
 > create (and thus get something that runs at the command-line more
 > conveniently).
 
 I'm satisfied enough with the kinds of
 programs they can write on their own
 machines with Racket installed.  I'm
 trying to give them a connection to the
 rest of the real world.
 
 --DGK
 
 
